h3. Issue Summary
Due to the migration of timezones associated with users, when the user timezone is not available in the "Working Days" section, the board settings page may brake.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Go to Atlassian account preferences - [direct link|https://id.atlassian.com/manage-profile/account-preferences?ref=jira&src=personalsettings];
 # Choose a timezone that is not available in the "Working Days" section of the board settings. Example: "America/Montreal";
# Create a board;

h3. Expected Results
The board will be created, and when going to the board settings page, users will be able to see the page formatted correctly.

h3. Actual Results
The board will be created, and when going to the board settings page, users aren't able to see the correct sections of the page.

Errors seen in the browser console:
{code}Uncaught TypeError: Cannot read property 'regionKey' of undefined{code}

h3. Workaround
For new boards: choose a similar timezone in the Atlassian account preferences that are available in the working days section in the board settings;
For existing boards: contact Atlassian Support;

h3. Issue Summary
In the new issue view, when users don't have access to sprints in a project, Jira skips the permissions and show all sprints for that field. In the old issue view, this doesn't happen. 

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Enable the new issue view;
 # Create two projects with different permission schemes, where one user should have access to one of the projects;
 # Create one sprint in each project;
 # In one of them, create an issue, open it and click in the sprint field;

h3. Expected Results
Only sprints where the user has permission to see will appear.

h3. Actual Results
Sprints for all projects will appear disregarding the permission scheme.

h3. Workaround
Deactivate the new issue view.

h3. Issue Summary

Column rename caused global status renaming.
h3. Steps to Reproduce

I sent mutation request to [https://api-private.atlassian.com/graphql]

 mutation renameColumn($input: SetColumnNameInput!) {
 {{  setColumnName(input: $input)}}{\{{}}

{{   statusCode}}

{{   success}}

   message   }

  }

{{}}}

 

{{This is input for this request}}

{
 {{  "input":}}

{     "boardId": "ari:cloud:jira-software:a436116f-02ce-4520-8fbb-7301462a1674:board/3165",     "columnId": "21548",     "columnName": "One"   }

{{}}}

 

This is the board I tried to change: [https://hello.atlassian.net/jira/software/projects/OC/boards/3165]
h3. Expected Results

Column on board 3165 renamed to "One"
h3. Actual Results

Besides column renaming mutation caused global status renaming (_All_ _other_ projects with workflow status "Open" were affected). 

Jira Admins received reports that queues in some projects were broken and the tickets they received had status of "One" instead of "Open".
h3. Workaround

Don't use `setColumnName` mutation?

h3. Issue Summary

Issue linking via Rest API does not honor the name and id of the issue link 

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Step 1: Create an issue with a different name but the same outward description and different inward description

 !image-2019-11-15-23-02-23-910.png|thumbnail! 
 # Step 2: Create issue with Rest API:

 {noformat}

//Create JSON body to create the issue
def requestBody = [
			fields: [
				summary    	: "TP-1-10002(Task)-Button",
				project: [
					key: "AAD"
				],
				issuetype: [
					id		: 10028
				],
			],
			update: [
            //Add an issue link during creation
			    issuelinks: [
			        [
			            add: [
			                type: [
			                    name: "Change Request"
			                ],
			                outwardIssue: [
			                    key: "AAD-34"
			                ]
			            ]
			        ]
			    ]
			]
		]

logger.info("About to make post (/rest/api/2/issue) with body: ${requestBody}")

//Create & link the issue, overriding screen security
def newIssue = post('/rest/api/2/issue').queryString("overrideScreenSecurity", Boolean.TRUE).header('Content-Type', 'application/json')
		.body(requestBody).asObject(Map) //Put requestBody into request and cast response to map (which triggers the running of the request)

{noformat}

#step 3: The issue has been successfully created:
{noformat}
  "body": {
    "id": "15734",
    "key": "AAD-54",
    "self": "https://hrconsultant.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issue/15734"
  }
}
{noformat}


h3. Expected Results

In json format the output should look like this:
{noformat}

issuelinks":[{"id":"10066","self":"https://hrconsultant.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issueLink/10066","type":{"id":"10108","name":"Change Request","inward":"Change Request","outward":"Direct Parent","self":"https://hrconsultant.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issueLinkType/10108"},"outwardIssue":{"id":"15643","key":"AAD-34","self":"https://hrconsultant.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issue/15643

{noformat}


h3. Actual Results

{noformat}
issuelinks":[{"id":"10066","self":"https://hrconsultant.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issueLink/10066","type":{"id":"10108","name":"Button","inward":"Buttons","outward":"Direct Parent","self":"https://hrconsultant.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issueLinkType/10108"},"outwardIssue":{"id":"15643","key":"AAD-34","self":"https://hrconsultant.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issue/15643
{noformat}

*In actual results, instead of showing change request, it is showing button but while creating issue link we used change request*

h3. Workaround
 Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

When creating an issue from within a board that has a component on its filter, that issue should inherit that component. For example:
* Filter of the board: {code}project = PROJ and component = "Component X"{code}
When creating the issue, it should inherit the "Component X" as its component.
